<collectingCountry box="[722,825,471,496]" name="Bermuda" pageId="6" pageNumber="501">Bermuda</collectingCountry>
(
<typeStatus box="[843,893,472,496]" pageId="6" pageNumber="501">type</typeStatus>
locality; 
<bibRefCitation author="Verrill" box="[1007,1149,471,496]" pageId="6" pageNumber="501" refString="Verrill, A. E. (1901) Additions to the fauna of the Bermudas from the Yale Expedition of 1901, with notes on other species. Transactions of the Connecticut Academy of Arts and Sciences, 11, 15 - 62." type="journal article" year="1901">
Verrill 
<number box="[1090,1149,472,496]" pageId="6" pageNumber="501" value="1901.0">1901</number>
</bibRefCitation>
), reported from 
<collectingCountry box="[1343,1436,472,496]" name="Curaçao" pageId="6" pageNumber="501">Curaçao</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Marcus" box="[158,435,508,533]" pageId="6" pageNumber="501" refString="Marcus, E. &amp; Marcus, E. (1968) Polycladida from Curacao and faunistically related regions. Studies on the Fauna of Curacao and other Caribbean Islands, 101, 1 - 133." type="journal article" year="1968">
Marcus &amp; Marcus 
<number box="[376,435,508,533]" pageId="6" pageNumber="501" value="1968.0">1968</number>
</bibRefCitation>
), Caribbean coast of 
<collectingCountry box="[678,788,508,533]" name="Colombia" pageId="6" pageNumber="501">Colombia</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Quiroga" box="[805,1046,508,533]" pageId="6" pageNumber="501" refString="Quiroga, S. Y., Bolanos, D. M. &amp; Litvaitis, M. K. (2004 b) A checklist of polyclad flatworms (Platyhelminthes: Polycladida) from the Caribbean coast of Colombia, South America. Zootaxa, 633, 1 - 12." type="journal article" year="2004" yearSuffix="b">
Quiroga 
<emphasis box="[907,965,508,533]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="501">et al.</emphasis>
<number box="[972,1032,508,533]" pageId="6" pageNumber="501" value="2004.0">2004</number>
b
</bibRefCitation>
), Florida, 
<collectingCountry box="[1164,1326,508,533]" name="Virgin Islands" pageId="6" pageNumber="501">Virgin Islands</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1338,1432,508,533]" name="Jamaica" pageId="6" pageNumber="501">Jamaica</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[151,225,543,568]" name="Belize" pageId="6" pageNumber="501">Belize</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[239,348,543,568]" name="Honduras" pageId="6" pageNumber="501">Honduras</collectingCountry>
and Caribbean coast of 
<collectingCountry box="[633,722,544,567]" name="Panama" pageId="6" pageNumber="501">Panama</collectingCountry>
(Rawlinson 
<number box="[871,931,544,568]" pageId="6" pageNumber="501" value="2008.0">2008</number>
), 
<collectingCountry box="[952,1020,543,568]" name="Brazil" pageId="6" pageNumber="501">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Bahia" box="[1038,1294,543,568]" pageId="6" pageNumber="501" refString="Bahia, J. &amp; Padula, V. (2009) First record of Pseudoceros bicolor and Pericelis cata (Platyhelminthes: Polycladida) from Brazil. Marine Biodiversity Records, 2, 1 - 5. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1017 / s 1755267209000918" type="journal article" year="2009">
Bahia &amp; Padula 
<number box="[1233,1294,544,568]" pageId="6" pageNumber="501" value="2009.0">2009</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). Specimens herein studied were found under rubbles in the intertidal and sublittoral zones.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="501" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,327,1000]" pageId="6" pageNumber="501">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,615,640]" pageId="6" pageNumber="501">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Dorsal coloration from yellow to dark brown, white spots present; white marginal band with greyish black transversal stripes; bright yellow to greenish marginal line sometimes present.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,327,1000]" pageId="6" pageNumber="501">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,454,687,712]" pageId="6" pageNumber="501">Taxonomic remarks.</emphasis>
<emphasis box="[470,712,687,712]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="501">
<taxonomicName box="[470,709,687,712]" class="Rhabditophora" family="Pseudoceritidae" genus="Pseudoceros" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polycladida" pageId="6" pageNumber="501" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="bicolor">Pseudoceros bicolor</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
described without histological sections (
<bibRefCitation author="Verrill" box="[1214,1363,687,712]" pageId="6" pageNumber="501" refString="Verrill, A. E. (1901) Additions to the fauna of the Bermudas from the Yale Expedition of 1901, with notes on other species. Transactions of the Connecticut Academy of Arts and Sciences, 11, 15 - 62." type="journal article" year="1901">
Verrill 
<number box="[1304,1363,688,712]" pageId="6" pageNumber="501" value="1901.0">1901</number>
</bibRefCitation>
), was amended by 
<bibRefCitation box="[307,567,724,749]" pageId="6" pageNumber="501" refString="Litvaitis, M. K., Bolanos, D. M. &amp; Quiroga, S. Y. (2010) When names are wrong and colours deceive: unraveling the Pseudoceros bicolor species complex (Turbellaria: Polycladida). Journal of Natural History, 44, 829 - 845. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1080 / 00222930903537074" type="journal article">
Litvaitis 
<emphasis box="[413,476,724,749]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="501">et al.</emphasis>
(
<number box="[497,559,724,748]" pageId="6" pageNumber="501" value="2010.0">2010</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
. These authors also studied the 
<emphasis box="[960,1071,724,749]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="501">P. bi co l o r</emphasis>
complex through a molecular approach. It was observed that specimens treated as a single species in papers such as Rawlinson (
<number box="[1250,1309,760,784]" pageId="6" pageNumber="501" value="2008.0">2008</number>
) and 
<bibRefCitation author="Bahia" pageId="6" pageNumber="501" refString="Bahia, J. &amp; Padula, V. (2009) First record of Pseudoceros bicolor and Pericelis cata (Platyhelminthes: Polycladida) from Brazil. Marine Biodiversity Records, 2, 1 - 5. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1017 / s 1755267209000918" type="journal article" year="2009">
Bahia &amp; Padula (
<number box="[272,331,796,820]" pageId="6" pageNumber="501" value="2009.0">2009</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
belong, in fact, to two distinct species with similar coloration pattern. The other species included in this complex is 
<taxonomicName authority="Bolanos, Quiroga &amp; Litvaitis, 2007" authorityName="Bolanos, Quiroga &amp; Litvaitis" authorityYear="2007" box="[357,1054,831,856]" class="Rhabditophora" family="Pseudoceritidae" genus="Pseudoceros" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polycladida" pageId="6" pageNumber="501" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="rawlinsonae">
<emphasis box="[357,645,831,856]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="501">Pseudoceros rawlinsonae</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Bolanos" box="[652,1054,831,856]" pageId="6" pageNumber="501" refString="Bolanos, D. M., Quiroga, S. Y. &amp; Litvaitis, M. K. (2007) Five new species of cotylean flatworms (Platyhelminthes: Polycladida) from the wider Caribbean. Zootaxa, 1650, 1 - 23." type="journal article" year="2007">
Bolaños, Quiroga &amp; Litvaitis, 
<number box="[994,1054,832,856]" pageId="6" pageNumber="501" value="2007.0">2007</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. We separated specimens in the 
<taxonomicName class="Rhabditophora" family="Pseudoceritidae" genus="Pseudoceros" kingdom="Animalia" order="Polycladida" pageId="6" pageNumber="501" phylum="Platyhelminthes" rank="species" species="bicolor">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="501">P. bicolor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
complex by considering 
<emphasis box="[531,640,868,893]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="501">P. b i c o l o r</emphasis>
the ones without marginal line or with a thin line bright yellow to greenish at the worm margin, as indicated by 
<bibRefCitation box="[657,897,903,928]" pageId="6" pageNumber="501" refString="Litvaitis, M. K., Bolanos, D. M. &amp; Quiroga, S. Y. (2010) When names are wrong and colours deceive: unraveling the Pseudoceros bicolor species complex (Turbellaria: Polycladida). Journal of Natural History, 44, 829 - 845. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1080 / 00222930903537074" type="journal article">
Litvaitis 
<emphasis box="[757,813,903,928]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="501">et al.</emphasis>
(
<number box="[827,889,904,928]" pageId="6" pageNumber="501" value="2010.0">2010</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
. Our immature specimens were of a smaller size (
<quantity box="[159,240,940,964]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.2" pageId="6" pageNumber="501" unit="mm" value="12.0">12 mm</quantity>
<date box="[247,282,940,964]" pageId="6" pageNumber="501">
x 
<quantity box="[268,282,940,964]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.0" pageId="6" pageNumber="501" unit="mm" value="9.0">9</quantity>
</date>
mm) than originally described (
<quantity box="[645,726,940,964]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="6" pageNumber="501" unit="mm" value="30.0">30 mm</quantity>
<date box="[733,782,940,965]" pageId="6" pageNumber="501" value="1915-10">
x 
<quantity box="[754,782,940,965]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="6" pageNumber="501" unit="mm" value="15.0">15</quantity>
</date>
mm), but they agree with features reported in the original description and recent amend (
<bibRefCitation author="Litvaitis" box="[494,720,975,1000]" pageId="6" pageNumber="501" refString="Litvaitis, M. K., Bolanos, D. M. &amp; Quiroga, S. Y. (2010) When names are wrong and colours deceive: unraveling the Pseudoceros bicolor species complex (Turbellaria: Polycladida). Journal of Natural History, 44, 829 - 845. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1080 / 00222930903537074" type="journal article" year="2010">
Litvaitis 
<emphasis box="[596,653,975,1000]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="501">et al.</emphasis>
<number box="[659,720,976,1000]" pageId="6" pageNumber="501" value="2010.0">2010</number>
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
